Exercise 1

Compute the bootstrap-based confidence interval for \(\mathtt{score}\) using the studentized method.

Solution We consider the \(\mathtt{score}\) dataset, as displayed below.

score <- read.table("student_score.txt", header = TRUE)

In particular, we are interested in the covariance matrix related to this dataset and the relevant eigenratio statistic.

cor(score)
##            mech      vecs       alg     analy      stat
## mech  1.0000000 0.4978075 0.7560364 0.6534763 0.5357744
## vecs  0.4978075 1.0000000 0.5922624 0.5071353 0.3786038
## alg   0.7560364 0.5922624 1.0000000 0.7627546 0.6698255
## analy 0.6534763 0.5071353 0.7627546 1.0000000 0.7376712
## stat  0.5357744 0.3786038 0.6698255 0.7376712 1.0000000
# define function to calculate eigenratio of cor(score)
psi_fun <- function(data) {
  eig <- eigen(cor(data), symmetric=TRUE, only.values=TRUE)$values
  return(max(eig) / sum(eig))
}
# compute observed eigenratio
psi_obs <- psi_fun(score)

In order to compute the bootstrap-based confidence interval with the studentized method, we use two procedures: 1. jackknife calculation to compute the standard error \(SE(\psi*)\), needed at each step of the bootstrap method 2. double bootstrap

The first procedure yields:

# number of iterations
B <- 10^4
n <- nrow(score)
pre_fact <- sqrt((n-1)/n)
# vector of statistics from resampling
s_vect <- rep(0, B)
# vector of standard error
SE_jack <- c()
z <- c()
time_jack <- system.time(
  for(i in 1:B) {
    ind <- sample(1:n, n, replace = TRUE)
    score2<- score[ind,]
    s_vect[i] <- psi_fun(score2)
    # jackknife in bootstrap
    psi_j <- c()
    for(j in 1:n) psi_j[j] <- psi_fun(score2[-j,])
    SE_jack[i] <- pre_fact*sqrt(sum((psi_j-mean(psi_j))^2))
  
    z[i]=(s_vect[i]-psi_obs)/SE_jack[i]
  }
)
SE_boot <- sd(s_vect)
# confidence intervals
studentized_ci_jack <- psi_obs - SE_boot*quantile(z,prob=c(0.95,0.05))
attr(studentized_ci_jack,"names") <- NULL
studentized_ci_jack
## [1] 0.5481378 0.8223991
# time requested to complete the task
time_jack
##    user  system elapsed 
##  35.710   0.004  35.717

The second procedure yields instead:

# number of iterations
C <- 10^4; C_loop <- 10^2
# vector of statistics from resampling
s_vect_2 <- rep(0, C)
# vector of standard error
SE_boot_i <- c()
z2 <- c()
time_dboot <- system.time(
  for(i in 1:C) {
    ind <- sample(1:n, n, replace = TRUE)
    score2<- score[ind,]
    s_vect_2[i] <- psi_fun(score2)
    # double bootstrap
    s_vect_loop <- rep(0, C_loop)
    for (j in 1:C_loop) {
      ind2 <- sample(1:n, n, replace = TRUE)
      score3 <- score2[ind2,]
      s_vect_loop[j] <- psi_fun(score3)
    }
    SE_boot_i[i] <- sd(s_vect_loop)
    
    z2[i]=(s_vect_2[i]-psi_obs)/SE_boot_i[i]
  }
)
SE_boot <- sd(s_vect_2)
# confidence intervals
studentized_ci_doubleboot <- psi_obs - SE_boot*quantile(z2,prob=c(0.95,0.05), na.rm = T)
attr(studentized_ci_doubleboot,"names") <- NULL
studentized_ci_doubleboot
## [1] 0.5469859 0.8465938
# time requested to complete the task
time_dboot
##    user  system elapsed 
## 167.904   0.000 167.920

We can observe that the second procedure gives wider intervals but processing takes longer compared with the first one.

Exercise 2

Compute bootstrap-based confidence intervals for the \(\mathtt{score}\) dataset using the \(\mathtt{boot}\) package.

Solution

We consider the previous dataset calculating the confidence intervals using the \(\mathtt{boot}\) package. To run it, the re-definition of psi_fun function is required.

psi_fun_boot <- function(data,indices) {
   d <- data[indices,]
   eig <- eigen(cor(d), symmetric=TRUE, only.values=TRUE)$values
   psi = max(eig)/sum(eig)
}
library(boot)

We compute the confidence intervals with the following code:

result_nostud <- boot(score, statistic=psi_fun_boot, R=10^4)
boot.ci(result_nostud,type="all")

## Level     Percentile            BCa          
## 95%   ( 0.5123,  0.8157 )   ( 0.5192,  0.8186 )  
## Calculations and Intervals on Original Scale

We notice that the studentized method was not performed. To compute also studentized confidence intervals we add a function which allow to compute the requested variances. Then, we define the function needed to generate all the requested types of confidence intervals.

library(magrittr)
library(purrr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'purrr'
## The following object is masked from 'package:magrittr':
## 
##     set_names
psi_fun_stud <- function(data,indices,its) {
  d <- data[indices,]
  eig <- eigen(cor(d), symmetric=TRUE, only.values=TRUE)$values
  v <- boot(d, statistic=psi_fun_boot, R=its)%>%pluck("t")%>%var(na.rm = TRUE)
  c(max(eig)/sum(eig),v)
}

At the end, confidence intervals are given by the following code:

result <- boot(score, statistic=psi_fun_stud, its=100, R=1000)
boot.ci(result,type="all")

Exercises LAB

Exercise 1

Compute the MLE and the observed information matrix for a gamma model with parameters shape \(\alpha\) and scale \(\beta\).

Solution

The probability distribution function for a gamma model with parameters \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) is \[f(y;\alpha,\beta)=\frac{\beta^{\alpha}}{\Gamma(\alpha)}y^{\alpha-1}e^{-\beta y}\] Then, the likelihood function is given by \[L(\alpha,\beta;y)=\prod_{i=1}^{n}f(\alpha,\beta;y_i)=\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{\beta^{\alpha}}{\Gamma(\alpha)}y_i^{\alpha-1}e^{-\beta y_i}\] from which one can compute the log-likelihood function as \[l(\alpha,\beta;y)=\log L(\alpha,\beta;y)=\alpha(n\log \beta) +(\alpha-1) \sum_{i=1}^n\log y_i-n\log\Gamma(\alpha)-\beta\sum_{i=1}^ny_i\] This can be computed using the following code.

log_like_gamma <- function(data,parameter){
  sum(dgamma(data, shape = parameter[1], rate = parameter[2], log = TRUE))
}

The previous quantity can be studied in a qualitative way by making contour plots.

# create data
n <- 15
y <- rgamma(15, shape = 9, rate = 4)
# create grid for parameters 
alpha <- seq(1, 25, length = 100)
beta <- seq(0.5, 10, length = 100)
parameter_values <- expand.grid(alpha, beta)
log_like_values <- apply(parameter_values, 1, log_like_gamma, data = y)
log_like_values <- matrix(log_like_values, nrow = length(alpha), ncol = length(beta), byrow = F)
confidence_levels <- c(0,0.5,0.75,0.9,0.95,0.99)
# create contour plot
contour(alpha, beta, log_like_values-max(log_like_values),
        levels = -qchisq(confidence_levels,2)/2, xlab = expression(alpha),
        labels = as.character(confidence_levels), ylab = expression(beta))
title('Gamma relative log likelihood')

First derivative of the log-likelihood function yields: \[\frac{\partial l}{\partial \alpha}=n\log\beta+\sum_{i=1}^n\log x_i-n\psi(\alpha)\] where \[\psi(\alpha)=\frac{\partial}{\partial \alpha}\log\Gamma(\alpha)=\frac{1}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\frac{\partial\Gamma(\alpha)}{\partial\alpha}\] and \[\frac{\partial l}{\partial \beta}=\frac{n\alpha}{\beta}-\sum_{i=1}^ny_i.\] Setting the latter equal to zero, one obtains \[\beta_{\alpha}=\frac{n\alpha}{\sum_{i=1}^n}\] which, substituted in derivative with respect to \(\alpha\) of the log-likelihood and putting it equal to zero, yields \[n\log\left(\frac{n\alpha}{\sum_{i=1}^n}\right)-n\psi(\alpha)+\sum_{i=1}^n\log y_i=0\] The last equation can be solved numerically to evaluate the MLE estimates with the following code.

# computing MLE
alpha_hat <- uniroot(function(x) n*log(n*x/sum(y))-n*digamma(x)+sum(log(y)), c(1e-15,25))$root
#alpha_hat
lambda_hat <- n*alpha_hat/sum(y)
#lambda_hat
c(alpha_hat, lambda_hat)
## [1] 12.725292  5.966237

In order to retrieve the observed information matrix, we employ the second derivative as follow: \[\frac{\partial^2 l}{\partial \alpha^2}=-n\frac{\partial}{\partial\alpha}\psi(\alpha)\] \[\frac{\partial l}{\partial\alpha\partial\beta}=\frac{n}{\beta}\] \[\frac{\partial^2 l}{\partial\beta^2}=-\frac{n\alpha}{\beta^2}\] Using this result in \(\mathtt{R}\) code:

# computing observed information matrix
j_matrix <- matrix(NA, nrow = 2, ncol = 2)
j_matrix[1,1] <- n*trigamma(alpha_hat)
j_matrix[1,2] <- j_matrix[2,1] <- -n/lambda_hat
j_matrix[2,2] <- n*alpha_hat/(lambda_hat^2)
solve(j_matrix)
##           [,1]     [,2]
## [1,] 21.040602 9.864859
## [2,]  9.864859 4.811611

Finally, the standard error are given by:

MLE_SE <- sqrt(diag(solve(j_matrix)))
MLE_SE
## [1] 4.587004 2.193538

Exercise 2

The Wald confidence interval with level \(1-\alpha\) is defined as:

\[ \hat{\gamma} \pm z_{1-\alpha/2}j_{P}(\hat{\gamma})^{-1/2}. \] Compute the Wald confidence interval of level 0.95, plot the results, and evaluate via simulation the empirical coverage of the confidence interval.

Solution

# define log likelihood function
log_lik_weibull <- function( data, param){
  -sum(dweibull(data, shape = param[1], scale = param[2], log = TRUE))
}

empirical_coverage <- c()
for(j in 1:10){
    M <- 10000; mat.ci <- matrix(NA, nrow = M, ncol = 2)
  for(i in 1:M){
    # generating data for simulation
    y_sim <- rweibull(15, shape = 7, scale = 155)
    # estimating for i-th simulation
    weib.y.mle_sim <- optim(c(1,1), fn=log_lik_weibull, hessian=T, method='L-BFGS-B',
                      lower=rep(1,2), upper=rep(Inf,2), data=y_sim)
    # extracting hessian
    h <- weib.y.mle_sim$hessian
    # estimation of standard error
    mle.se_sim <- sqrt(diag(solve(h)))
    # computation of i-th confidence interval
    mat.ci[i,] <- weib.y.mle_sim$par[1] + qnorm(0.975)*mle.se_sim[1]*c(-1,1)
  }
  # empirical coverage of the confidence interval 
  empirical_coverage[j] <- mean(mat.ci[,1] < 7 & mat.ci[,2] > 7, na.rm = T)
}
empirical_coverage
##  [1] 0.9507 0.9540 0.9525 0.9489 0.9511 0.9491 0.9542 0.9477 0.9510 0.9505

The result above shows that the probability to find the exact value of the parameter inside the computed confidence interval can be well approximated by a standard normal distribution.

Exercise 3

Repeat the steps above write the profile log-likelihood, plot it and find the deviance confidence intervals considering this time \(\gamma\) as a nuisance parameter and \(\beta\) as the parameter of interest.

Solution

The profile log likelihood for \(\beta\) is: \[l_{P}(\beta) = \underset{\gamma}{\max}\ l(\gamma, \beta; y)\] However, in this case, we dont have a closed form for the MLE estimate of \(\beta\) given \(\gamma\) and therefore we must resort to numerical optimization: for each value of \(\beta\) we compute the MLE estimate for the parameter \(\gamma\).

n <- 15
y <- rweibull(n, shape = 7, scale = 155)
log_lik_weibul <- function(data, gamma, beta){
  -sum(dweibull(data, shape = gamma, scale = beta, log = TRUE))
}

beta <- seq(110, 200, length.out = 100)
profile_lik <- vector(length=100)

for (i in 1:100) {
  profile_lik[i] <- nlm(log_lik_weibul, c(5), data=y, beta=beta[i])$minimum
}

The plot of the profile log-likelihood is given by:

plot(beta, -profile_lik-max(-profile_lik), type="l", ylab="profile likelihood")

We plot now the confidence intervals.

conf.level <- 0.95

# confidence interval
for (i in 1:100) {
  if ( profile_lik[i] == min(profile_lik)) i_max <- i
}
beta_hat <- beta[i_max]
gamma_hat <- uniroot(function(x) n/x + sum(log(y)) -n*log(beta_hat) - n*sum((y/beta_hat)^x*log(y/beta_hat)), c(1,15))$root

hess <- optimHess(c(gamma_hat,beta_hat),log_lik_weibull,data=y)
J_obs_to_minus1 <- solve(hess)
se_wald_95 <- sqrt(J_obs_to_minus1[2,2])

wald_95 <- beta_hat + c(-1,1)*qnorm(0.975)*se_wald_95

y_text_1 <- -nlm(log_lik_weibul, c(5), data=y, beta=wald_95[1])$minimum-max(-profile_lik)
y_text_2 <- -nlm(log_lik_weibul, c(5), data=y, beta=wald_95[2])$minimum-max(-profile_lik)

plot(beta, -profile_lik-max(-profile_lik), type="l", ylab="profile likelihood")
segments( wald_95[1], (y_text_1+y_text_2)/2, wald_95[2], (y_text_1+y_text_2)/2, col="red", lty =1, lwd=2  )
text(beta_hat,(y_text_1+y_text_2)/2-1,"Wald-type 95% confidence interval",col=2)

segments( wald_95[1],1, wald_95[1],
          -30, col="red", lty=2)
segments( wald_95[2],1, wald_95[2],
          -30, col="red", lty=2)

points(wald_95[1], y_text_1, pch=16, col=2, cex=1.5)
points(wald_95[2], y_text_2, pch=16, col=2, cex=1.5)

Finally, we compute the empirical coverage of the \(95\%\) Wald-type confidence interval:

M <- 10000; mat.ci <- matrix(NA, nrow = M, ncol = 2)
for(i in 1:M){
  # generating data for simulation
  y_sim <- rweibull(15, shape = 7, scale = 155)
  # estimating for i-th simulation
  weib.y.mle_sim <- optim(c(1,1), fn=log_lik_weibull, hessian=T, method='L-BFGS-B',
                      lower=rep(1,2), upper=rep(Inf,2), data=y_sim)
  # extracting hessian
  h <- weib.y.mle_sim$hessian
  # estimation of standard error
  mle.se_sim <- sqrt(diag(solve(h)))
  # computation of i-th confidence interval
  mat.ci[i,] <- weib.y.mle_sim$par[2] + qnorm(0.975)*mle.se_sim[2]*c(-1,1)
}
# empirical coverage of confidence interval
mean(mat.ci[,1] < 155 & mat.ci[,2] > 155, na.rm = T)
## [1] 0.9146
#input values
#true mean
theta_sample <- 2
#likelihood variance
sigma2 <- 2
#sample size
n <- 10
#prior mean
mu <- 7
#prior variance
tau2 <- 2

#generate some data
set.seed(123)
y <- rnorm(n,theta_sample, sqrt(sigma2))

#posterior mean
mu_star <- ((1/tau2)*mu+(n/sigma2)*mean(y))/( (1/tau2)+(n/sigma2))
#posterior standard deviation
sd_star <- sqrt(1/( (1/tau2)+(n/sigma2)))

library(rstan)
#launch Stan model
data<- list(N=n, y=y, sigma =sqrt(sigma2), mu = mu, tau = sqrt(tau2))
fit <- stan(file="normal.stan", data = data, chains = 4, iter=2000)
#extract Stan output
sim <- extract(fit)

Exercise 4

In \(\mathsf{sim}\) in the code above, you find the MCMC output which allows to approximate the posterior distribution of our parameter of interest with \(S\) draws of \(\theta\). Plot the empirical cumulative distribution function and compare it with the theoretical cumulative distribution function of the posterior distribution.

Solution

library(MASS)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
x <- seq(1,4,length.out=100)
# Plot of the cdf of the posterior distribution of theta simulated by MCMC
plot(x, ecdf(sim$theta)(x), xlab=expression(theta), main=expression(paste("CDF of",theta)))
# true analytical posterior
curve(pnorm(x, mu_star, sd_star), col="blue", lwd=2, add=T)


# qqplot of the MCMC quantile and analytical quantile
x <- rnorm(100, mu_star, sd_star)
qqplot(ecdf(sim$theta)(x), pnorm(x, mu_star, sd_star), main=expression(paste("qqplot of ", theta)),
       xlab="MCMC quantile", ylab="expected quantile")
v = seq(0, 1, length.out = 100)
lines(v,v, col="blue", lwd=2, )

From both the plot of the empirical cdf and the qqplot we see that the random draws provided by MCMC simulation are distributed in the same way as the draws from the true analytical posterior distribution.

Exercise 5

Launch the following line of \(\mathsf{R}\) code:

posterior <- as.array(fit, )

Use now the \(\mathsf{bayesplot}\) package. Read the help and produce for this example, using the object posterior, the following plots:

  • posterior intervals.
  • posterior areas.
  • marginal posterior distributions for the parameters.

Quickly comment.

Solution

library(bayesplot)
## This is bayesplot version 1.7.2
## - Online documentation and vignettes at mc-stan.org/bayesplot
## - bayesplot theme set to bayesplot::theme_default()
##    * Does _not_ affect other ggplot2 plots
##    * See ?bayesplot_theme_set for details on theme setting
posterior <- as.array(fit)

# Posterior intervals of the parameter theta
mcmc_intervals(posterior, pars = "theta", prob_outer = 0.95) +
  ggplot2::labs(
   title = expression(paste("Posterior interval of ", theta)),
   subtitle = "Bold line: 50% interval. Thin line: 95% interval"
 )

# Posterior areas of the parameter theta
mcmc_areas(posterior, pars = "theta", prob=0.95) +
  ggplot2::labs(
   title = expression(paste("Posterior areas of ", theta)),
   subtitle = "with median and 95% intervals"
 )

# Posterior distribution of both the parameter theta and lp__
mcmc_dens(posterior) +
  ggplot2::labs(
   title = "Posterior distribution of the parameters"
 )

In this case, we have only one parameter \(\theta\) which represents the posterior mean of the distribution. The functions used allow us to change easily the desired confidence interval on the variables, using the prob or prob_outer parameters, while the pars parameter lets us choose which parameters to plot. If we dont specify to plot \(\theta\) with pars="theta", the function plots also another parameter \(lp\_\_\), which is linked to the log-posterior and automatically given by the MCMC simulation. We only plot \(lp\_\_\) the last graph when showing the marginal distributions of the parameters, since if we plot it in the other graphs they will be too zoomed out (because \(lp\_\_ \approx -24\) and \(\theta \approx 3\)) and we wont see clearly the confidence intervals on the parameter of interest \(\theta\).

Exercise 6

Suppose you receive \(n = 15\) phone calls in a day, and you want to build a model to assess their average length. Your likelihood for each call length is \(y_i \sim \mathsf{Poisson}(\lambda)\). Now, you have to choose the prior \(\pi(\lambda)\). Please, tell which of these priors is adequate to describe the problem, and provide a short motivation for each of them:

  1. \(\pi(\lambda)= \mathsf{Beta}(4,2)\);

  2. \(\pi(\lambda)= \mathsf{Normal}(1,2)\);

  3. \(\pi(\lambda)=\mathsf{Gamma}(4,2)\);

Now, compute your posterior as \(\pi(\lambda|y)\propto L(\lambda;y)\pi(\lambda)\) for the selected prior. If your first choice was correct, you will be able to compute it analitically.

Solution

  1. The beta distribution is defined in the interval \([0,1]\); so we are assuming that our phone calls will not last longer than 1 minute. However our likelihood is a Poisson distribution which has support in \([0,+\infty]\) and therefore we could have some observations that will fall out of bounds of the prior distribution. This evidence leads us to discard the beta prior distribution.

  2. The normal distribution is defined in the interval (\(-\infty\),\(+\infty\)) which means that our phone calls can have negative length (no sense, to be discarded). To make it useful, we have to consider a truncated normal distribution which is equal to \(0\) in \([-\infty,0]\)).

  3. The gamma distribution has the same support of our likelihood function \([0,+\infty]\), this leads us to consider this distribution as the prior distribution. In our case \(\mathsf{Gamma}(4,2)\) has mean \(2\) and standard deviation \(1\): so we are assuming that the average length of our phone calls will be near \(2\). Another property of the gamma distribution is that it is the conjugate prior for the Poisson likelihood function, as can be seen with some simple algebra:

\[L(\lambda;\boldsymbol{y})\pi(\lambda) = \prod_{i=1}^n\bigg[\mathsf{Pois}(\lambda; y_i)\bigg]\mathsf{Gamma}(\lambda;\alpha, \beta) \propto e^{-n\lambda}\lambda^{\sum_{i=1}^{n} y_i} \lambda^{\alpha-1}e^{-\beta\lambda} = \lambda^{\alpha + \sum_{i=1}^{n} y_i} e^{-(\beta+n)\lambda}\]

The last expression represents a \(\mathsf{Gamma}(\sum_{i=1}^{n} y_i + \alpha, \beta+n)\) distribution, the mean of the distribution takes the form: \[\hat \lambda = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} y_i + \alpha}{\beta + n} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} y_i}{\beta+n} + \frac{\alpha}{\beta+n} = \frac{n}{\beta+n}\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} y_i}{n} + \frac{\beta}{\beta+n} \frac{\alpha}{\beta}\]

From the last expression we can clearly see that the greater the number of observations, the more the posterior mean tends to the sample mean, as expected.

Exercise 7

Go to this link: rstan, and follow the instructions to download and install the \(\mathsf{rstan}\) library. Once you did it successfully, open the file model called \(\mathsf{biparametric.stan}\), and replace the line:

\[\mathsf{ target+=cauchy\_lpdf(sigma| 0, 2.5);} \]

with the following one:

\[\mathsf{ target+=uniform\_lpdf(sigma| 0.1, 10);} \]

Which prior are you now assuming for your parameter \(\sigma\)? Reproduce the same plots as above and briefly comment.

Solution

I am assuming for the parameter \(\sigma\) a uniform prior distribution between \(0.1\) and \(10\),

#launch biparametric Stan model

data3 <- list(N=n, y=y, a=-10, b=10)
fit3 <- stan(file="biparametric.stan", data = data3, chains = 4, iter=2000,
  refresh=-1)

#extract stan output for biparametric model

sim3 <- extract(fit3)
posterior_biv <- as.matrix(fit3)

theta_est <- mean(sim3$theta)
sigma_est <- mean(sim3$sigma)
c(theta_est, sigma_est)
traceplot(fit3, pars=c("theta", "sigma"))

plot_title <- ggtitle("Posterior distributions",
                      "with medians and 80% intervals")

mcmc_areas(posterior_biv, 
           pars = c("theta","sigma"), 
           prob = 0.8) + plot_title

Since we are assuming a uniform prior distribution for \(\sigma\) all the values between \(0.1\) and \(10\) are equally possible, this leads to fatter tails of both the \(\sigma\) and \(\theta\) distribution. The fact that the distribution of \(\theta\) changes is pretty interesting and is hinting us that the parameters \(\sigma\) and \(\theta\) arent really independent: in fact, if high values of \(\sigma\) are less penalized we are more likely to have a wider distribution. We could choose \(\theta\) to be farther from the sample mean, which in turn leads to a heavier tailed distribution for \(\theta\). Another difference which arise using an uniform distribution instead of the Cauchy distribution is that we are bounding the sigma parameter between \(0.1\) and \(10\). However, values greater than \(10\) or less than \(0.1\) are very unlikely from the beginning, and therefore, in the practice, this constraint does not impact.

Exercise 8

Simulate a sample of size \(n=14\) from a Bernoulli distribution parameter \(p=0.5\).

  • Looking at the \(\mathsf{Stan}\) code for the other models, write a short \(\mathsf{Stan}\) Beta-Binomial model, where \(p\) has a \(\mathsf{Beta}(a,b)\) prior with \(a=3\), \(b=3\).

  • extract the posterior distribution with the function \(\mathsf{extract()}\);

  • produce some plots with the \(\mathsf{bayesplot}\) package and comment.

  • compute analitically the posterior distribution and compare it with the \(\mathsf{Stan}\) distribution.

Solution

The stan file for this simulation is:

 data{
  int<lower=0> N;
  int y[N];
  real a;
  real b;
 }
 parameters{
  real p;
 }
 model{
  target += bernoulli_lpmf(y | p);
  target += beta_lpdf(p | a, b);
 }

We didnt set the parameters in the stan file because we will provide them through R.

Now we run the MCMC simulation

## Simulates with Rstan the above model

## Input values
# true probability
p <- 0.5
# parameters of the prior distribution
a <- 3
b <- 3
# sample size
n <- 14
# generate some data
y <- rbinom(n, 1, p)

# Launch Stan model
library(rstan)
data <- list(N=n, y=y, a=a, b=b)
fit <- stan(file="beta-binomial.stan", data=data, chains=4, iter=2000)

extract Stan output

sim <- extract(fit)

and produce posterior intervals, areas and distribution plots using the \(\mathsf{bayesplot}\) package

library(bayesplot)
posterior <- as.array(fit)

# Posterior intervals of the parameter theta
mcmc_intervals(posterior, pars = "p", prob_outer = 0.95) +
  ggplot2::labs(
   title = expression(paste("Posterior interval of ", theta)),
   subtitle = "Bold line: 50% interval. Thin line: 95% interval"
 )

# Posterior areas of the parameter theta
mcmc_areas(posterior, pars = "p", prob=0.95) +
  ggplot2::labs(
   title = expression(paste("Posterior areas of ", theta)),
   subtitle = "with median and 95% intervals"
 )

# Posterior distribution of both the parameter theta and lp__
mcmc_dens(posterior) +
  ggplot2::labs(
   title = "Posterior distribution of the parameters"
 )

We observe that the posterior distribution of the parameter is very wide, both due to the small amount of observation that we have and because \(\mathsf{Beta}(3,3)\) prior is quite flat near \(0.5\) (as shown in the graph below)

curve(dbeta(x, 3,3), col="blue", lwd=2, ylab = "Beta(3,3)")

We now compare the MCMC posterior draws with the analytical posterior distribution

a_post <- a + sum(y)
b_post <- b + n - sum(y)

library(MASS)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
# histogram of the posterior distribution of theta simulated by MCMC
hist.scott(sim$p, prob=TRUE, xlab = expression(theta), main=expression(paste("Histogram of ", theta)))
# true analytical posterior
curve(dbeta(x, a_post, b_post), col="blue", lwd=2, add=T)


# qqplot of the MCMC quantile and analytical quantile
x <- rbeta(100, a_post, b_post)
qqplot(ecdf(sim$p)(x), pbeta(x, a_post, b_post), main=expression(paste("qqplot of ", theta)),
       xlab="MCMC quantile", ylab="expected quantile")
v = seq(0, 1, length.out = 100)
lines(v,v, col="blue", lwd=2, )

From both the histogram and the qqplot above we see that the random draws provided by MCMC simulation are distributed in the same way as the draws from the true analytical distribution.
